body:
Consider the following example:
```systemverilog
module reduction;
  typedef struct { int x, y; } point_t;

  initial begin
    int sum_squares, multiplied_sum_squares;
    point_t q[$] = '{point_t'{1, 2}, point_t'{2, 3}};
    int extra_multipliers[$] = '{};

    sum_squares = q.sum with (item.x * item.x + item.y * item.y);
    multiplied_sum_squares = extra_multipliers.product * sum_squares;

    $display("Sum of squared lengths: %0d", sum_squares);
    $display("Multiplied sum of squared lengths: %0d", multiplied_sum_squares);
    $finish;
  end
endmodule
```

This will produce an error (shortened):
```gcc
/mnt/more/Documents/verilator/include/verilated_types.h:837:43: error: no match for ‘operator+=’ (operand types are ‘Vreduction_reduction__DOT__point_t__struct__0’ and ‘unsigned int’)
  837 |         for (const auto& i : m_deque) out += with_func(index++, i);
      |                                       ~~~~^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~                              ~~~~^~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
```

because the return type of call to `sum` method is different than item's type.

Additionally in this example, I call `product` on an empty queue. I could not find anything that would address this case in the specs. Currently we return zero, but I think it makes more sense to return a neutral element instead. This also lets us simplify the code a bit. Fortunately for us, the current SystemVerilog specification does not permit operator overloading, meaning that we can easily construct such elements using integers.

While fixing those issues, I also noticed a small bug in one of the existing implementations regarding `index` variable.

------------------

Changes introduced by this PR:

* Fix return type for calls with `with` clause
* Fix missing index incrementation for `.and with` calls
* ~~For zero-length aggregates return neutral element, which depending on the operation can be something different than 0.~~
